## 1933 murder case

In 1933, the press's history took a lurid turn. David Lamson, a sales manager at SUP, was accused of murdering his wife, Allene, in their home on the Stanford campus. The case became a local sensation. The novelist and poet [Janet Lewis](/Janet_Lewis), in a move of civic engagement, wrote a pamphlet arguing for Lamson's acquittal, highlighting the profound risks of relying on circumstantial evidence. After the ordeal of four separate trials, Lamson was ultimately set free. A bit of true crime to spice up the publishing history.

